            <h1>You Clicked a Simulated Phishing Link</h1>
        </div>

        <section>
            <div class="sectionText">
                <h2>Don't worry, your data is safe. This was a training exercise.</h2>
                <p>You clicked on a simulated phishing link created by your organization as part of security awareness training. No harm was done, and no information was collected beyond training results.</p>
                <p>Cybercriminals design phishing emails to look convincing and create urgency, curiosity, or trust. Many intelligent and experienced people click them every day.</p>
                <p>What matters most is learning how to spot them more quickly next time.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section>
            <div class="sectionText">
                <h2>Why This Email May Have Looked Legitimate</h2>
                <p>Phishing emails are designed to imitate normal business communication. They often use familiar branding, realistic formatting, and believable requests.</p>
                <p>Common tactics include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Urgent deadlines ("Act now" / "Your account will be locked")</li>
                    <li>Requests from leadership or IT staff</li>
                    <li>Fake invoices or shared documents</li>
                    <li>Security alerts or password reset notices</li>
                    <li>Unexpected attachments or links</li>
                    <li>Slightly altered sender addresses</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="comparing">
                <img src="/media/microsoft-legitReasons.png"
                    alt="A legitimate email from Microsoft">
                <img src="/media/Microsoft_spoofReasons.png"
                    alt="A phishing email mimicking Microsoft">
            </div>
        </section>

        <section>
            <div class="sectionText">
                <h2>Warning Signs to Look For</h2>
                <h3>Suspicious Sender Address</h3>
                <p>The display name may look familiar, but the real email address is different.</p>
                <p>Example: IT Support &lt;support-companysecure.com&gt; instead of your real company domain.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="example">
                <img src="/media/google-spoofReasons.png"
                    alt="Example of a spoofed sender address">
            </div>
        </section>

        <section>
            <div class="sectionText">
                <h2>Urgent or Emotional Language</h2>
                <p>Phishing messages often pressure you to act immediately.</p>
                <p>Examples:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>"Your account will expire today."</li>
                    <li>"Immediate action required."</li>
                    <li>"Final warning."</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section>
            <div class="sectionText">
                <h2>Unexpected Links or Attachments</h2>
                <p>If you were not expecting a file, invoice, shared document, or login request, be cautious.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="example">
                <img src="/media/sharedDoc-spoofReasons.png"
                    alt="Example of a suspicious shared document email">
            </div>
        </section>

        <section>
            <div class="sectionText">
                <h2>Hovering Shows a Different Link</h2>
                <p>A button may say one thing but lead somewhere else. Always hover over links before clicking.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="example">
                <img src="/media/sharedDoc-spoofReasons.png"
                    alt="Example showing hover reveals different link destination">
            </div>
        </section>

        <section>
            <div class="sectionText">
                <h2>What To Do Before Clicking</h2>
                <p>Use the <strong>Pause – Inspect – Verify</strong> method.</p>
                <h3>1. Pause</h3>
                <p>Take a moment before reacting to urgency.</p>
                <h3>2. Inspect</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Sender address</li>
                    <li>Spelling and grammar</li>
                    <li>Link destination</li>
                    <li>Whether the request is expected</li>
                </ul>
                <h3>3. Verify</h3>
                <p>If unsure, contact the sender through a trusted method such as Teams, phone, or the official company directory.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section>
            <div class="sectionText">
                <h2>What To Do If You Click a Real Suspicious Link</h2>
                <p>If this had been a real phishing attempt:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Close the page immediately</li>
                    <li>Do not enter credentials</li>
                    <li>Disconnect from suspicious downloads</li>
                    <li>Report the email to IT / Security</li>
                    <li>Change your password if credentials were entered</li>
                    <li>Follow your organization's reporting process</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section>
            <div class="sectionText">
                <h2>Quick Habits That Prevent Most Phishing</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>Slow down when an email feels urgent</li>
                    <li>Double-check sender addresses</li>
                    <li>Hover before clicking links</li>
                    <li>Be cautious with attachments</li>
                    <li>Verify unusual requests through another channel</li>
                    <li>Report suspicious emails promptly</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="finalSection">
            <div class="sectionText">
                <h2>Final Reminder</h2>
                <p>Phishing attacks succeed because they are designed to exploit normal human behavior like trust, speed, and helpfulness. With practice, recognizing them becomes faster and easier.</p>
                <p>Thank you for helping keep your organization secure.</p>
            </div>
